   =20
 =20
Most of what investment banks do is pitching. Sometimes an unsolicited tran=
saction will show up at their door: A hedge fund will call to say =E2=80=9C=
hey I was thinking about buying some derivatives, do you have any,=E2=80=9D=
 an asset manager will call to say =E2=80=9Chey I own a billion dollars of =
bonds I don=E2=80=99t want anymore, will you buy them,=E2=80=9D a corporate=
 client will call to say =E2=80=9Chey I want to do a merger, what looks goo=
d,=E2=80=9D etc. But every time you get 10 minutes between inbound inquirie=
s, you are pitching, or thinking up things to pitch. You dream up the deriv=
ative and then call the hedge fund to buy it. Clients mostly make money by=
=C2=A0owning things; banks mostly make money by=C2=A0making transactions ha=
ppen. The banks are the ones who want the transactions to happen, so they=
=E2=80=99re the ones suggesting the transactions.One good way to pitch some=
one on selling something is to call them up and say =E2=80=9Chey we have a =
motivated buyer for that thing you own, you should sell it, you=E2=80=99ll =
get a good price.=E2=80=9D One good way to pitch someone on buying somethin=
g is to call them up and say =E2=80=9Chey we have a motivated seller of tha=
t thing you like, you should buy it, you=E2=80=99ll get a good price.=E2=80=
=9D And so if you walk into work one day and the phones aren=E2=80=99t ring=
ing, a thing you could do is:=09Call a hedge fund.=09Say =E2=80=9Chey if we=
 had some X at a good price would you buy it?=E2=80=9D=09They say =E2=80=9C=
sure I guess I dunno.=E2=80=9D=09Hang up and call an asset manager who owns=
 a lot of X.=09Say =E2=80=9Chey we have gotten some reverse inquiry on X, p=
eople really want to buy it and we could get you a good price, are you inte=
rested?=E2=80=9D=09They say =E2=80=9Csure I guess I dunno.=E2=80=9D=09Call =
the first hedge fund back. =E2=80=9CI think I can get you some of that X th=
at you really wanted.=E2=80=9D=09Keep calling them until there=E2=80=99s a =
trade.=09Collect a spread.This is, however, a bit of a tricky business. Whe=
n you say =E2=80=9CI think I can get you some of that X that you really wan=
ted,=E2=80=9D the hedge fund might hear something more like =E2=80=9CI have=
 a customer who is desperate to sell as much X as they can.=E2=80=9D The he=
dge fund might go and sell X short, figuring that the price will go down (a=
nd that it will be able to buy from you to cover its short). The hedge fund=
=E2=80=99s shorting might have the effect of=C2=A0driving=C2=A0the price do=
wn, and thus reducing the price that the asset manager can get for its X. T=
he asset manager might get annoyed: =E2=80=9CEvery time I talk to you about=
 X the price goes down, which costs me money.=E2=80=9DWe  talked yesterday =
about a Justice Department probe into block trading by banks=E2=80=99 equit=
y trading desks. Bloomberg News  has more today:U.S. authorities are examin=
ing the involvement of one of Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s top equities executi=
ves in block trades as part of an investigation into whether banks improper=
ly alerted certain clients to market-moving transactions, according to peop=
le with knowledge of the matter.Pawan Passi, who ran Morgan Stanley=E2=80=
=99s U.S. equity syndicate desk and led the firm=E2=80=99s communications w=
ith investors for equity transactions, is among individuals whose activitie=
s are facing scrutiny, the people said, asking not to be identified describ=
ing the confidential inquiry. Bloomberg reported in November that the compa=
ny had put Passi on leave.I am still unclear what they are actually investi=
gating but here are some hints:To gauge demand from buyers and potentially =
gin up interest from sellers, bankers send out lists of shares with upcomin=
g lockup expirations, according to market participants. It=E2=80=99s essent=
ially an invitation to hedge funds and family offices to express interest i=
n buying, even if banks don=E2=80=99t have a mandate yet. The practice is c=
onsidered legal.Sometimes, bankers also engage in hypothetical conversation=
s with buyers before they have a mandate. Asking prospective buyers whether=
 they might be interested in certain stocks is one thing. But if there are =
indeed plans afoot for block sales, such conversations, even phrased hypoth=
etically, can tip off savvy money managers. While there is technically no t=
ransfer of material non-public information -- the usual line for running af=
oul of U.S. laws -- market participants describe it as a gray area.=C2=A0Se=
llers have long complained about block trades that seemed to be preceded by=
 stock drops, hurting their proceeds when they cash out. And buyers complai=
n that hedge funds agreeing to participate in purchases may seek special tr=
eatment from the banks in future transactions -- such as getting stock allo=
cated to them in highly sought-after IPOs.=C2=A0You can see how this might =
get murky. If the head of equity syndicate at Morgan Stanley calls up a hed=
ge fund and says =E2=80=9Chey hypothetically would you be interested in Sto=
ck X,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0that is informative; it suggests that a block of Stock =
X might be coming, which will drive down the price, so the hedge fund might=
 as well short it. This is true if Morgan Stanley is mandated to sell the b=
lock (in which case it wouldn=E2=80=99t be chatting hypothetically but=C2=
=A0actually asking for orders), or if Morgan Stanley is in informal talks w=
ith a potential seller about the block (in which case leaking to potential =
buyers is arguably poor form), or even=C2=A0if Morgan Stanley has never tal=
ked to the potential seller in its life. Because if Morgan Stanley is canva=
ssing interest, it=E2=80=99s doing that=C2=A0so that it can go pitch the po=
tential seller on a trade: =E2=80=9CHey, we=E2=80=99ve been hearing from he=
dge funds that they want to buy your Stock X, we can get you a good price, =
let=E2=80=99s go.=E2=80=9D And Morgan Stanley is good at this business, so =
if you are a hedge fund getting those calls then you can assume a block tra=
de is more likely. Just knowing that Morgan Stanley is pitching the trade i=
s informative.Also apparently  this is Archegos-related:=C2=A0Morgan Stanle=
y=E2=80=99s role in the unraveling of=C2=A0Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s family offi=
ce breathed new life into a federal probe examining irregularities in Wall =
Street=E2=80=99s lucrative market for block trades.U.S. authorities ramped =
up their investigation into whether big banks and their hedge fund clients =
broke rules when privately negotiating large stock sales after the blowup a=
t=C2=A0Archegos Capital Management, according to people with knowledge of t=
he matter. =E2=80=A6Federal investigators began focusing on the trades carr=
ied out by New York-based Morgan Stanley that occurred a day before a much =
broader fire sale of Archegos=E2=80=99s holdings led to more than $35 billi=
on of value being wiped out from those shares -- the start of a broader rou=
t in the equities that took hold in the weeks ahead.That led to a wider ins=
pection of multiple trades brought to market by Morgan Stanley, and whether=
 its clients illegally profited from trading in advance of those transactio=
ns. That has also led to scrutiny of=C2=A0Pawan Passi, a senior executive a=
t the bank who spoke frequently with clients about various block trades.A f=
un fact about  the Archegos blowup is that Archegos  owned most of its shar=
es on swap, meaning that it=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t own them; it just had cash-=
settled derivatives contracts with its banks giving it economic exposure to=
 those shares. The banks hedged those swaps by owning the shares themselves=
, for their own account. So if a bank called up a hedge fund and said =E2=
=80=9Chey hypothetically would you be interested in buying some shares of V=
iacomCBS Inc.,=E2=80=9D I am not sure it would be betraying any customer in=
formation: It would technically just be looking to=C2=A0sell its own shares=
.[1] Surely it=E2=80=99s not illegal to look for buyers for stock you own?
