   =20
      Margin loan
   =20
 =20
Meanwhile I feel like there are people who work at big investment banks who=
 spend 50% of their time calling Masayoshi Son to pitch crazy ideas, and th=
e other 50% of their time hoping that he won=E2=80=99t call them to pitch c=
razy ideas. Son does lots of wild stuff, which I am sure is fun and lucrati=
ve for his banks when they dream it up, but=C2=A0inbound inquiry from him=
=C2=A0 is trouble:SoftBank Group Corp. is asking banks jostling for roles o=
n a potential listing of Arm Ltd. to underwrite a margin loan of about $8 b=
illion, according to people familiar with the matter.=C2=A0The margin loan =
financing -- linked to Arm=E2=80=99s IPO stock -- is one option under consi=
deration as SoftBank lines up an advisory roster for what could be the year=
=E2=80=99s biggest initial public offering, the people said, asking not to =
be named as the details aren=E2=80=99t public.Banks are planning to pitch I=
PO valuations for Arm of upward of $50 billion, the people said. Arm is lik=
ely worth $25 billion to $35 billion based on the industry=E2=80=99s valuat=
ion metrics and analysts=E2=80=99 early projections, Bloomberg reported thi=
s month. Nvidia=E2=80=99s collapsed attempt to buy Arm for a combination of=
 cash and stock was worth about $40 billion when announced in 2020 and rose=
 to more than $60 billion as the bidder=E2=80=99s shares climbed.The way  I=
PO pitches basically work is that the bankers all write very high numbers o=
n pieces of paper, and then the client gives the mandate to the bank who wr=
ites the highest number, because that bank seems enthusiastic about the com=
pany and best positioned to tell its story. And then the bank gets to work =
on (1) talking the company up to investors and (2) talking that number=C2=
=A0down=C2=A0to the client. And then eventually the IPO launches and prices=
 and the valuation is=C2=A0whatever the market says it is; the number the b=
ank wrote down in its pitch doesn=E2=80=99t matter at all. The bank is not=
=C2=A0held=C2=A0to that number. The bank is not going to=C2=A0buy the IPO=
=C2=A0at that number. That=E2=80=99s just flattery.On the other hand if you=
 come into the meeting and say =E2=80=9Cthis company is worth $60 billion, =
we are very confident of that, hire us,=E2=80=9D and SoftBank says =E2=80=
=9Csure, no problem, if you lend us $8 billion at a 50% loan-to-value on th=
at valuation,=E2=80=9D that is awkward! It is not quite the same as asking =
you to buy the IPO at that price, but it is=C2=A0related. You=E2=80=99re no=
t going to give SoftBank an $8 billion margin loan unless you are confident=
 that=C2=A0your collateral is worth at least, you know, $16 billion or what=
ever, which requires you to have a real, non-flattery-based view on valuati=
on. It=E2=80=99s one thing to pitch an IPO at a high valuation; it=E2=80=99=
s another thing to put $8 billion of your own money into it.
