   =20
      The GameStop thing
   =20
 =20
Last January, GameStop Corp.=E2=80=99s stock went up 1,625% on huge volume =
with lots of volatility for  no obvious reason. It was the leading story in=
 national news for days, and by mid-February there were at least eight movi=
e and TV projects about it in the works. Since then GameStop has given back=
 many, though certainly not all, of its gains; it started 2021 at $18.84, e=
nded January 2021 at $325, and closed yesterday at $126.16.Why did this hap=
pen? There are, I think, four main lines of explanation:=09A lot of retail =
investors got together on Reddit and said =E2=80=9Cwe like the stock.=E2=80=
=9D They bought the stock, so it went up. They bought the stock from value-=
driven institutional investors, who liked the stock up to a certain price b=
ut not higher. Once all the value-driven investors were out of the stock an=
d only retail investors (and insiders and index funds) were left, there was=
 no real cap on the price, so it kept going up as people kept having more f=
un. All of this seems true and is obviously at least part of the explanatio=
n, but it also feeds into other, more debatable, more arcane explanations.=
=09At the start of January 2021, a lot of hedge funds were short GameStop s=
tock. When the people on Reddit got together to buy GameStop and the price =
started going up, those hedge funds lost money and had to liquidate their s=
hort positions. This required them to buy back the stock they had shorted, =
which pushed the price up further. This is called a =E2=80=9Cshort squeeze.=
=E2=80=9D=09The people on Reddit didn=E2=80=99t just buy stock; they also b=
ought call options. If you buy a call option from an options dealer, the de=
aler will go out and buy some of the underlying stock to hedge =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0often buying more stock (in dollars) than you paid the dealer in premium=
. So buying call options is a=C2=A0levered=C2=A0way to buy stock; you buy m=
ore stock for your dollars and thus push the price up more. Also, as the pr=
ice goes up, the dealer has to buy even=C2=A0more=C2=A0stock to remain hedg=
ed, which pushes the price up even more even if you don=E2=80=99t keep buyi=
ng more call options. This is called a =E2=80=9Cgamma squeeze.=E2=80=9D=09S=
ome other, darker, weirder explanation. =E2=80=9CActually the hedge funds a=
re manipulating GameStop up for their own profit,=E2=80=9D that sort of thi=
ng.The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission looked into it and published=
 a report last October. The report was  a little disappointing in that it d=
idn=E2=80=99t really find evidence for anything except Explanation 1, peopl=
e on Reddit liking the stock. There was some short covering and some gamma,=
 but those things didn=E2=80=99t seem too material to the price moves. It w=
ould be satisfying if there was some clear technical explanation of what ha=
ppened, but the basic takeaway from the SEC report was =E2=80=9Cyeah market=
s are weird sometimes and when everyone buys a stock it goes up.=E2=80=9DOt=
hers  disagree:Meme-stock mania might have been a case of traders banding t=
ogether to take down hedge funds after all. =C2=A0That=E2=80=99s the conten=
tion of new research that challenges the Securities and Exchange Commission=
=E2=80=99s view that a so-called short squeeze played little part in pushin=
g GameStop Corp. into the stratosphere in January 2021. The regulator faile=
d to examine relevant securities-lending data and didn=E2=80=99t study a lo=
ng enough stretch of transactions, a half a dozen academics from Columbia U=
niversity, the University of Notre Dame and elsewhere asserted in a paper s=
ent in recent weeks to SEC Chair Gary Gensler.=C2=A0 ...=E2=80=9CThe SEC=E2=
=80=99s October analysis used incomplete data and flawed methods to reach e=
rroneous conclusions regarding the events of January 2021,=E2=80=9D said Jo=
shua Mitts, lead author of the study and a Columbia University law professo=
r. Our =E2=80=9Cfindings suggest that the SEC=E2=80=99s response to GameSto=
p and other meme stocks may be deeply misguided.=E2=80=9DThe SEC also fell =
short, according to the paper, in examining the effects of a so-called gamm=
a squeeze, which occurs when options dealers buy a rising stock to balance =
their exposure to contracts they have sold, pushing shares even higher. The=
 SEC focused on call contracts in its analysis, while overlooking the effec=
t of put contracts, which can contribute to gamma squeezes, the academics s=
aid.=C2=A0Here is the report. It is not what you would call a smoking gun o=
r anything, but it argues that short positions (and short-equivalent put-op=
tion positions) were higher than the SEC counted, and therefore short cover=
ing made up more of the volume in GameStop during its crazy week. In partic=
ular it estimates that short covering made up more than 20% of GameStop=E2=
=80=99s volume on Jan. 28 and Jan. 29, 2021. It also estimates that options=
 hedging =E2=80=94=C2=A0a gamma squeeze =E2=80=94=C2=A0might have made up a=
s much as another 20% of volume some days. If almost half of the buying in =
GameStop on its craziest days came from these technical factors, then that =
would be interesting.I don=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99d do about it th=
ough? There is an argument that either of these things =E2=80=94=C2=A0coord=
inating on Reddit to intentionally squeeze shorts, or to buy call options t=
o induce hedging activity by dealers =E2=80=94=C2=A0might be =E2=80=9Cmarke=
t manipulation=E2=80=9D; you are buying stocks (or options) not in a bet on=
 their intrinsic worth but to try to force other market participants to act=
. Market manipulation is a slippery concept, and I think it would be hard t=
o distinguish =E2=80=9Cbuying stock to cause a short squeeze=E2=80=9D from =
"buying stock that you think will go up,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbuying option=
s to cause a gamma squeeze=E2=80=9D from =E2=80=9Cbuying options on a stock=
 that you think will go up.=E2=80=9D Though, sure, typing on Reddit =E2=80=
=9Clet=E2=80=99s do a short squeeze and a gamma squeeze=E2=80=9D helps with=
 that distinction.As it is, the main regulatory response to the GameStop th=
ing seems to be that U.S. stock markets will  move to T+1 settlement. There=
 is some tinkering with the plumbing, but not a fundamental rethinking of w=
hat went on during the GameStop mania.=C2=A0Which seems fine to me, honestl=
y. People liked the stock so it went up; weird stuff happens. But what is t=
he SEC=C2=A0for?=C2=A0Somewhere on its list of priorities, arguably there s=
hould be one like =E2=80=9Cmarkets should be set up in such a way that pric=
es are likely to reflect fundamental values.=E2=80=9D This is hard to do an=
d hard to evaluate,=C2=A0and you do not want the SEC dictating fundamental =
value. And yet. If you look at an event where that manifestly did not happe=
n, where everyone gleefully went around buying stock at prices they did not=
 think reflected fundamental value, that probably does call for some sort o=
f regulatory nervousness at least.I don=E2=80=99t know what that means for =
SEC regulation of crypto, by the way! Imagine trying to make sure that the =
market for Dogecoin reflects its fundamental value. Perhaps best not to mak=
e this a priority.
