<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Block trades</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most of what investment banks do is pi=
tching. Sometimes an unsolicited transaction will show up at their door: A =
hedge fund will call to say =E2=80=9Chey I was thinking about buying some d=
erivatives, do you have any,=E2=80=9D an asset manager will call to say =E2=
=80=9Chey I own a billion dollars of bonds I don=E2=80=99t want anymore, wi=
ll you buy them,=E2=80=9D a corporate client will call to say =E2=80=9Chey =
I want to do a merger, what looks good,=E2=80=9D etc. But every time you ge=
t 10 minutes between inbound inquiries, you are pitching, or thinking up th=
ings to pitch. You dream up the derivative and then call the hedge fund to =
buy it. Clients mostly make money by=C2=A0<em>owning things</em>; banks mos=
tly make money by=C2=A0<em>making transactions happen</em>. The banks are t=
he ones who want the transactions to happen, so they=E2=80=99re the ones su=
ggesting the transactions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One good way to =
pitch someone on selling something is to call them up and say =E2=80=9Chey =
we have a motivated buyer for that thing you own, you should sell it, you=
=E2=80=99ll get a good price.=E2=80=9D One good way to pitch someone on buy=
ing something is to call them up and say =E2=80=9Chey we have a motivated s=
eller of that thing you like, you should buy it, you=E2=80=99ll get a good =
price.=E2=80=9D And so if you walk into work one day and the phones aren=E2=
=80=99t ringing, a thing you could do is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: =
decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Call a hedge fund.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Say =E2=
=80=9Chey if we had some X at a good price would you buy it?=E2=80=9D</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They say =E2=80=9Csure I guess I dunno=
.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hang up and call an ass=
et manager who owns a lot of X.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sa=
y =E2=80=9Chey we have gotten some reverse inquiry on X, people really want=
 to buy it and we could get you a good price, are you interested?=E2=80=9D<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They say =E2=80=9Csure I guess I d=
unno.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Call the first hedg=
e fund back. =E2=80=9CI think I can get you some of that X that you really =
wanted.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Keep calling them=
 until there=E2=80=99s a trade.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Co=
llect a spread.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, however, a b=
it of a tricky business. When you say =E2=80=9CI think I can get you some o=
f that X that you really wanted,=E2=80=9D the hedge fund might hear somethi=
ng more like =E2=80=9CI have a customer who is desperate to sell as much X =
as they can.=E2=80=9D The hedge fund might go and sell X short, figuring th=
at the price will go down (and that it will be able to buy from you to cove=
r its short). The hedge fund=E2=80=99s shorting might have the effect of=C2=
=A0<em>driving=C2=A0</em>the price down, and thus reducing the price that t=
he asset manager can get for its X. The asset manager might get annoyed: =
=E2=80=9CEvery time I talk to you about X the price goes down, which costs =
me money.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTUveW91LWdldC10aGUtY3J5cHRvLX=
J1bGVzLXlvdS1wYXktZm9yP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09Z=
W1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249=
bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf11df4db" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked yesterday=
</a> about a Justice Department probe into block trading by banks=E2=80=99 =
equity trading desks. Bloomberg News <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTYvbW9yZ2FuLXN0YW5sZXktcy1wYXNzaS1pcy1zYWlkLXRvLWZ=
hY2UtdS1zLWJsb2NrLXRyYWRpbmctcHJvYmU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjE2JnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7a655d2" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> has=
 more today</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">U.S. authoriti=
es are examining the involvement of one of Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s top equ=
ities executives in block trades as part of an investigation into whether b=
anks improperly alerted certain clients to market-moving transactions, acco=
rding to people with knowledge of the matter.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Pawan Passi, who ran Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s U.S. equity syndicate desk=
 and led the firm=E2=80=99s communications with investors for equity transa=
ctions, is among individuals whose activities are facing scrutiny, the peop=
le said, asking not to be identified describing the confidential inquiry. B=
loomberg reported in November that the company had put Passi on leave.</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am still unclear what they are a=
ctually investigating but here are some hints:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">To gauge demand from buyers and potentially gin up interest=
 from sellers, bankers send out lists of shares with upcoming lockup expira=
tions, according to market participants. It=E2=80=99s essentially an invita=
tion to hedge funds and family offices to express interest in buying, even =
if banks don=E2=80=99t have a mandate yet. The practice is considered legal=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes, bankers also engage in hypothe=
tical conversations with buyers before they have a mandate. Asking prospect=
ive buyers whether they might be interested in certain stocks is one thing.=
 But if there are indeed plans afoot for block sales, such conversations, e=
ven phrased hypothetically, can tip off savvy money managers. While there i=
s technically no transfer of material non-public information -- the usual l=
ine for running afoul of U.S. laws -- market participants describe it as a =
gray area.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sellers have long complain=
ed about block trades that seemed to be preceded by stock drops, hurting th=
eir proceeds when they cash out. And buyers complain that hedge funds agree=
ing to participate in purchases may seek special treatment from the banks i=
n future transactions -- such as getting stock allocated to them in highly =
sought-after IPOs.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You c=
an see how this might get murky. If the head of equity syndicate at Morgan =
Stanley calls up a hedge fund and says =E2=80=9Chey hypothetically would yo=
u be interested in Stock X,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>that is informative</em>; it =
suggests that a block of Stock X might be coming, which will drive down the=
 price, so the hedge fund might as well short it. This is true if Morgan St=
anley is mandated to sell the block (in which case it wouldn=E2=80=99t be c=
hatting hypothetically but=C2=A0<em>actually asking for orders</em>), or if=
 Morgan Stanley is in informal talks with a potential seller about the bloc=
k (in which case leaking to potential buyers is arguably poor form), or eve=
n=C2=A0if Morgan Stanley has never talked to the potential seller in its li=
fe. Because if Morgan Stanley is canvassing interest, it=E2=80=99s doing th=
at=C2=A0so that it can go pitch the potential seller on a trade: =E2=80=9CH=
ey, we=E2=80=99ve been hearing from hedge funds that they want to buy your =
Stock X, we can get you a good price, let=E2=80=99s go.=E2=80=9D And Morgan=
 Stanley is good at this business, so if you are a hedge fund getting those=
 calls then you can assume a block trade is more likely. Just knowing that =
Morgan Stanley is pitching the trade is informative.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Also apparently <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjItMDItMTYvbW9yZ2FuLXN0YW5sZXktcy1hcmNoZWdvcy11bndpbmRpbmctc3BlZC11cC=
1ibG9jay10cmFkaW5nLXByb2JlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpd=
W09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFp=
Z249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53ef98f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this is Arch=
egos-related</a>:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Morgan =
Stanley=E2=80=99s role in the unraveling of=C2=A0Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s famil=
y office breathed new life into a federal probe examining irregularities in=
 Wall Street=E2=80=99s lucrative market for block trades.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">U.S. authorities ramped up their investigation into whether =
big banks and their hedge fund clients broke rules when privately negotiati=
ng large stock sales after the blowup at=C2=A0Archegos Capital Management, =
according to people with knowledge of the matter. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Federal investigators began focusing on the trades carried=
 out by New York-based Morgan Stanley that occurred a day before a much bro=
ader fire sale of Archegos=E2=80=99s holdings led to more than $35 billion =
of value being wiped out from those shares -- the start of a broader rout i=
n the equities that took hold in the weeks ahead.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">That led to a wider inspection of multiple trades brought to market =
by Morgan Stanley, and whether its clients illegally profited from trading =
in advance of those transactions. That has also led to scrutiny of=C2=A0Paw=
an Passi, a senior executive at the bank who spoke frequently with clients =
about various block trades.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A =
fun fact about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/267=
31524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
EtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEM=
DIxNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXIm=
dXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB6f67a3c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> the Archegos blowup</a> is that Archegos <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zL=
WFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhcmQtZm9yLWJhbmtzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAy=
MTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB68536c78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> owned most of its shares on swap</a>, meaning that it=
=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t </em>own them; it just had cash-settled derivative=
s contracts with its banks giving it economic exposure to those shares. The=
 banks hedged those swaps by owning the shares themselves, for their own ac=
count. So if a bank called up a hedge fund and said =E2=80=9Chey hypothetic=
ally would you be interested in buying some shares of ViacomCBS Inc.,=E2=80=
=9D I am not sure it would be betraying any customer information: It would =
technically just be looking to=C2=A0<em>sell its own shares</em>.[1] Surely=
 it=E2=80=99s not illegal to look for buyers for stock you own?</p><table c=
