oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">at least eight<=
/a> movie and TV projects about it in the works. Since then GameStop has gi=
ven back many, though certainly not all, of its gains; it started 2021 at $=
18.84, ended January 2021 at $325, and closed yesterday at $126.16.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why did this happen? There are, I think, four main=
 lines of explanation:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-le=
ft: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A lot of re=
tail investors got together on Reddit and said =E2=80=9Cwe like the stock.=
=E2=80=9D They bought the stock, so it went up. They bought the stock from =
value-driven institutional investors, who liked the stock up to a certain p=
rice but not higher. Once all the value-driven investors were out of the st=
ock and only retail investors (and insiders and index funds) were left, the=
re was no real cap on the price, so it kept going up as people kept having =
more fun. All of this seems true and is obviously at least part of the expl=
anation, but it also feeds into other, more debatable, more arcane explanat=
ions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At the start of January 2021=
, a lot of hedge funds were short GameStop stock. When the people on Reddit=
 got together to buy GameStop and the price started going up, those hedge f=
unds lost money and had to liquidate their short positions. This required t=
hem to buy back the stock they had shorted, which pushed the price up furth=
er. This is called a =E2=80=9Cshort squeeze.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">The people on Reddit didn=E2=80=99t just buy stock; the=
y also bought call options. If you buy a call option from an options dealer=
, the dealer will go out and buy some of the underlying stock to hedge =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0often buying more stock (in dollars) than you paid the dealer i=
n premium. So buying call options is a=C2=A0<em>levered=C2=A0</em>way to bu=
y stock; you buy more stock for your dollars and thus push the price up mor=
e. Also, as the price goes up, the dealer has to buy even=C2=A0<em>more=C2=
=A0</em>stock to remain hedged, which pushes the price up even more even if=
 you don=E2=80=99t keep buying more call options. This is called a =E2=80=
=9Cgamma squeeze.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some ot=
her, darker, weirder explanation. =E2=80=9CActually the hedge funds are man=
ipulating GameStop up for their own profit,=E2=80=9D that sort of thing.</l=
i></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion looked into it and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9zdGFmZi1yZXBvcnQtZ=
XF1aXR5LW9wdGlvbnMtbWFya2V0LXN0cnVjdGlvbi1jb25kaXRpb25zLWVhcmx5LTIwMjEucGRm=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB86207e17" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">published a report</a> last Oct=
ober. The report was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjEtMTAtMTkvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1nYW1lc3RvcC1iYWZmbGVzLXR=
oZS1zZWMtdG9vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf4ade281" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a little disappointing<=
/a> in that it didn=E2=80=99t really find evidence for anything except Expl=
anation 1, people on Reddit liking the stock. There was some short covering=
 and some gamma, but those things didn=E2=80=99t seem too material to the p=
rice moves. It would be satisfying if there was some clear technical explan=
ation of what happened, but the basic takeaway from the SEC report was =E2=
=80=9Cyeah markets are weird sometimes and when everyone buys a stock it go=
es up.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Others <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTQvbWVtZS1zdG9jay1mcmVuenktZ2V0c=
y1hLWZyZXNoLWxvb2stdGhhdC1xdWVzdGlvbnMtc2VjLW5hcnJhdGl2ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE2=
MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1=
fdGVybT0yMjAyMTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
a9771ae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> disagree</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Meme-stock mania might have been a case of traders banding together to tak=
e down hedge funds after all. =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=
=E2=80=99s the contention of new research that challenges the Securities an=
d Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s view that a so-called short squeeze played =
little part in pushing GameStop Corp. into the stratosphere in January 2021=
. The regulator failed to examine relevant securities-lending data and didn=
=E2=80=99t study a long enough stretch of transactions, a half a dozen acad=
emics from Columbia University, the University of Notre Dame and elsewhere =
asserted in a paper sent in recent weeks to SEC Chair Gary Gensler.=C2=A0 .=
..</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe SEC=E2=80=99s October analy=
sis used incomplete data and flawed methods to reach erroneous conclusions =
regarding the events of January 2021,=E2=80=9D said Joshua Mitts, lead auth=
or of the study and a Columbia University law professor. Our =E2=80=9Cfindi=
ngs suggest that the SEC=E2=80=99s response to GameStop and other meme stoc=
ks may be deeply misguided.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SE=
C also fell short, according to the paper, in examining the effects of a so=
-called gamma squeeze, which occurs when options dealers buy a rising stock=
 to balance their exposure to contracts they have sold, pushing shares even=
 higher. The SEC focused on call contracts in its analysis, while overlooki=
ng the effect of put contracts, which can contribute to gamma squeezes, the=
 academics said.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26731524.281600/a=
HR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQwMzAx=
Nzk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98de6527" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the report</a>. It is not wh=
at you would call a smoking gun or anything, but it argues that short posit=
ions (and short-equivalent put-option positions) were higher than the SEC c=
ounted, and therefore short covering made up more of the volume in GameStop=
 during its crazy week. In particular it estimates that short covering made=
 up more than 20% of GameStop=E2=80=99s volume on Jan. 28 and Jan. 29, 2021=
. It also estimates that options hedging =E2=80=94=C2=A0a gamma squeeze =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0might have made up as much as another 20% of volume some days. =
If almost half of the buying in GameStop on its craziest days came from the=
se technical factors, then that would be interesting.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99d do about it though? Ther=
e is an argument that either of these things =E2=80=94=C2=A0coordinating on=
 Reddit to intentionally squeeze shorts, or to buy call options to induce h=
edging activity by dealers =E2=80=94=C2=A0might be =E2=80=9Cmarket manipula=
tion=E2=80=9D; you are buying stocks (or options) not in a bet on their int=
rinsic worth but to try to force other market participants to act. Market m=
anipulation is a slippery concept, and I think it would be hard to distingu=
ish =E2=80=9Cbuying stock to cause a short squeeze=E2=80=9D from "buying st=
ock that you think will go up,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbuying options to cause=
 a gamma squeeze=E2=80=9D from =E2=80=9Cbuying options on a stock that you =
think will go up.=E2=80=9D Though, sure, typing on Reddit =E2=80=9Clet=E2=
=80=99s do a short squeeze and a gamma squeeze=E2=80=9D helps with that dis=
tinction.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As it is, the main regulatory res=
ponse to the GameStop thing seems to be that U.S. stock markets will <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26731524.281600/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTAvcHJpdmF0ZS1=
mdW5kcy1hcmUtdGhlLW5ldy1wdWJsaWMtZnVuZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRk=
YmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjE2J=
nV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7c3fd011" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 move to T+1 settlement</a>. There is some tinkering with the plumbing, but=
 not a fundamental rethinking of what went on during the GameStop mania.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which seems fine to me, honestly. Peopl=
e liked the stock so it went up; weird stuff happens. But what is the SEC=
=C2=A0<em>for</em>?=C2=A0Somewhere on its list of priorities, arguably ther=
e should be one like =E2=80=9Cmarkets should be set up in such a way that p=
rices are likely to reflect fundamental values.=E2=80=9D This is hard to do=
 and hard to <em>evaluate</em>,=C2=A0and you do not want the SEC dictating =
fundamental value. And yet. If you look at an event where that manifestly d=
id not happen, where everyone gleefully went around buying stock at prices =
they did not think reflected fundamental value, that probably does call for=
 some sort of regulatory nervousness at least.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what that means for SEC regulation of crypto, by t=
he way! Imagine trying to make sure that the market for Dogecoin reflects i=
ts fundamental value. Perhaps best not to make this a priority.</p><table c=
